Doc Spatz ,<br><br>
Let's be realistic, this site was far from utopia in the past.  There were plenty of personal attacks, hurtful words, terrible language, angry people, irrational dialog, people speaking but NOT LISTENING etc.  Just review old postings and you will see.  How many people left here just because they grew weary of the same old scenarios.  Not all of the original crowd was a bargain either.  Remember Doc, there were times when this dialog would be dead for a week or more.  In regards to some (notice I said some-not all) of the original posters, it doesn't bother me to see them gone.  Like anything else, sometimes a dialog gets played out, ideas wrung dry by a particular crowd, then what is left?  No one carries a conversation forever, no carries a dialog forever.<br><br>
One thing I do miss here though is the discussion on hard hitting, emotional topics, like  PTSD,  agent orange -right or wrong?, reality of combat, difficulties of service in Nam/Nam period, etc. That is what drew many to this site initially (it drew me).  That is what we need again, or perhaps everyone is weary of talking about these things.  Let's face it, this site certainly didn't have a friendly, &quot;welcome aboard&quot; attitude at all times.  How many people were driven away?  Few agreed than and few agree now, the nature of Vietnam discussion in America.<br><br>
So now, what we have here is a group of vets who have come here to talk about Vietnam, perhaps &quot;socialize&quot;.  Yes, it is far from nail biting suspense.  Yes, I don't always like the inner circle or veterans only things, EVERYONE has a right to an opinion on Vietnam, Not just those who served.  I was born until 1974, but my father was a combat vet, and like it or not I have the right to speak on Vietnam.  Yes, vets brag about war, yes some people may not like it, but they have the right to do it.  This site is for discussion, it can only be a discussion among those who show up here.  How many people have you chased away? <br><br>
 Yes, this site could and should be more focused to specific topics.  Perhaps the posters here should BRAINSTORM a list a topics they would like to see (A technique I picked up from teaching).  Doc, try creating a topic and posting on it, instead of fighting all the time.  Save the fighting for a topic, something with goals, not a unguided war (didn't Vietnam teach you anything).<br><br>
I have two further points:<br>
1.  I take NO sides here.<br>
2.  I have one piece of advice for all posters here:  In the words of former Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger more than 20 years ago, &quot;Everyone is entitled to his own views, but everyone is not entitled to his own facts.&quot; <br><br>
To Ed-unfortunately there is NO sacred ground on-line, it just doesn't happen.<br>
         
